INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'cc8e7793-1286-48f9-85cc-997c25cfe6e7',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$gRPC Resolvers — Killing the N+1 Problem with DataLoader and Server Streaming$escape$,
  $escape$When GraphQL resolvers call gRPC services, each field resolution triggers a Unary RPC — spinning up an HTTP/2 stream per call. A list of 100 posts each resolving an author fires 100 separate `GetUser` Unary RPCs. DataLoader collapses this: within a single event-loop tick it batches all `load()` calls and issues one `ListUsersByIds` ServerStream RPC instead.

Define a batch RPC in your `.proto` accepting repeated IDs and streaming back results. The DataLoader batch function iterates the async stream, builds a lookup map, and returns values in the exact order DataLoader requires. Missing IDs return an `Error` instance — DataLoader surfaces these as per-item rejections, not a thrown exception, so one bad ID doesn't poison the batch.

For GraphQL subscriptions backed by gRPC, map them directly to ServerStream RPCs. Your subscription resolver returns an `AsyncIterator` that yields values as the stream emits. Unlike polling Unary calls, the HTTP/2 connection stays open — no reconnection overhead, and backpressure is handled natively by gRPC's flow-control window.

Schema tip: model paginated lists as `Connection` types to avoid over-fetching; gRPC's page-token streaming maps cleanly to GraphQL cursor-based pagination.$escape$,
  $escape$const userLoader = new DataLoader<string, User>(async (ids) => {
  const stream = userClient.listUsersByIds({ ids: ids as string[] });
  const map = new Map<string, User>();
  for await (const user of stream) {
    map.set(user.id, user);
  }
  return ids.map(id => map.get(id) ?? new Error(`User ${id} not found`));
});

const resolvers = {
  Post: {
    author: ({ authorId }: Post) => userLoader.load(authorId),
  },
};$escape$,
