INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'f67b56bc-9dca-4137-a4bf-bc0321520ed1',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$gRPC Performance — Squeeze More Out of Payload Size, Compression, and Multiplexing$escape$,
  $escape$gRPC's performance edge comes from four compounding wins: Protobuf binary encoding, HTTP/2 multiplexing, header compression, and persistent connections.

Protobuf is already compact, but field numbers matter. Fields with default values are omitted on the wire — design your messages so hot paths hit defaults often. For large payloads (>1 KB), enable gzip or gzip-equivalent compression at the channel level; gRPC-Go exposes `grpc.WithDefaultCallOptions(grpc.UseCompressor(gzip.Name))` on the client.

HTTP/2 multiplexes multiple RPCs over a single TCP connection, eliminating head-of-line blocking from HTTP/1.1. Avoid creating a new `ClientConn` per request — share one conn across goroutines; it's safe and designed for it. For server-side fan-out, use client-streaming or bidirectional-streaming RPCs rather than N unary calls.

Keep-alive probes (`keepalive.ClientParameters`) prevent idle connections from being silently dropped by load balancers. Set `Time: 30s`, `Timeout: 10s`, and `PermitWithoutStream: true` for long-lived stubs. On the server, mirror with `keepalive.EnforcementPolicy` to avoid GOAWAY storms.$escape$,
  $escape$import (
    "google.golang.org/grpc"
    "google.golang.org/grpc/encoding/gzip"
    "google.golang.org/grpc/keepalive"
    "time"
)

conn, err := grpc.NewClient(
    "api.example.com:443",
    grpc.WithDefaultCallOptions(grpc.UseCompressor(gzip.Name)),
    grpc.WithKeepaliveParams(keepalive.ClientParameters{
        Time:                30 * time.Second,
        Timeout:             10 * time.Second,
        PermitWithoutStream: true,
    }),
)$escape$,
  $escape$go$escape$,
